When one of these women becomes a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate."
“Young and healthy women also remain spared as they help with work and give birth to children,” a nun describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso in a special home for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their communities.
The local government has now decided to act against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he published a pamphlet designed to prevent the "witch-stalking".
But the thing has a hook.
“More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” the Standard newspaper pointed to the dilemma of written enlightenment.
