The architects looked in - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that comes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known buildings in Brno come, counted from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building on the premises for his company’s mini-garden.
In wise anticipation, because most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is committed to having the designers return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the opportunity to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
It is easier for civil engineers and architects to put their demanding profession and childcare under one roof.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operating kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (grants amounting to CZK 2.8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for the duration of 2 years is provided for qualified personnel and for the operation.
After the exhaustion of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing effective assistance in the processing of applications.
The children are taken care of by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is still comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool lessons, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus eliminates the stress of late picking up the children from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also formed here.
Arch.Design was thus one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof mutes like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are torn up fish molars.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "bone house".
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splitters and mosaics, the scale-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that one notices that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting enhances the brightness of the colors.
The same swinging lines and intertwined shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, and even look holes and slats.
The House of Batll<0xC3><0xB3> in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia No. 43 was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, designed by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper renovation.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> rental house, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, many other painters and artists also collaborated in the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> in the Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Shortly after its completion, the house received its organic forms from the local inhabitants because of the nickname "bone house".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gaining house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed for the house a central heating system unique for the time with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
A bit bizarre is already mutating her 45-degree inclination.
During his work, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was not fooled by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he made about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so dismayed by the result that they demanded reparation two years later.
Among other things, the councillors also objected to the fact that the building, with its pillars, even intervened in the public pavement.
However, there were no changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request in this regard, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> submitted an application for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a company lounge, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey building runs a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the reconstruction, all right angles and straight lines were eliminated and replaced by curved and curved walls.
But Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two other floors, in addition to a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, through Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s renovation.
Also impressive is Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courtyards.
The play of these two colors gives all the floors of the house a maximum level of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> house, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The owners of the house decided to take this step only in the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this is a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, yes they were extended to other common rooms and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not cardboard, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist ID cards get a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed rest? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the bedding - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
When choosing, many things play a role - the weight, size, state of health and not least the gender of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior in which mattress and rust must be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend home where it is not regularly heated, latex mattresses are not well suited, as they take much longer to “get warm”.
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they do not have enough venting ducts in the core and are still lying on a solid plate, moisture builds up: It is not excluded that mold forms under them.
Of course, the choice also plays a role in what you are used to.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, it will be difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
“Although all the ice hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can’t sleep properly here anymore.”
"For their abraded shoulders, heels and hips, they just need a soft layer of visco foam (Memory Foam - a shape-memory polymer)."
"I also recommend this among other things to people with diabetes who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can poorly receive the "information" from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamczikov<0xC3><0xA1>, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That’s why I bought these mattresses with visco foam (Memory Foam) for many ice hockey players, but also other customers, years ago.
"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don’t necessarily have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it flatters directly on the warm body.
Nowhere does it push, at night you do not roll around like after a hard fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also provides protection against decubitus (wund fire).
When choosing the mattress size, the length of the soles should still be added to the body size, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Both men and women, who are 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm of lying width, so together 180 cm.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For convenience and also for any visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal width of the bed: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough room for the slightly angled arms", advises Ing. Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, the master of the upholsterers and interior designer, who has been devoting herself for years to the problems of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own lattice and their own mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are also the same height.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the grille in different heights and this is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be on the mold layer and the fine padding.
"You can't feel the feathers by hand or sitting down," warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a special type of rust.
Fully upholstered beds with mattresses and underlays such as grown-up Siamese twins have nothing to look for in the bedroom.
These mattresses can not be ventilated and the cover can not be washed, which is already happening today.
And since one loses between 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged) screen after five to seven years.
This is also why professionals reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years, even a lifetime warranty, for mattresses.
Every thing has its When and But.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of washable, detachable covers, but it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which can be easily removed and washed.
Even though mattress covers are usually made today with a round zipper, so that after opening you get two halves (immeasurably important for the washing process and the size of the washing machine!), manipulation with larger mattresses, especially alone, often takes place like the unequal fight between David and Goliath.
Do they have a fixed plate in bed instead of a grid?
Get out of here!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Also, they should prefer to provide the plate with ventilation holes (if they are not already in it) and mattresses with a spring skeleton and a minimum height of 15 cm with so-called pocket spring cores and fine cushions.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a substrate.
For non-adjustable lattice grids with 14 to 18 spring bars (lamellae) latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), always pay for grids with a larger number of lattices, i.e. 28 and more spring bars, with Lordoses support in the lumbar vertebral region and the possibility to adjust the lattice hardness.
Adjustable lamella grids do not include mattresses with a spring skeleton, as they do not respond to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press the spring strips or even to bend them in such a way that they allow the shoulder of the sleeper to sink in punctually.
Especially for men with wide shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have begun to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
The ladies are also thought of - they are granted these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point elastic wing spring systems (Latoflex) or lattice with point elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion springs are intended.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the voltage.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and proper rust, most of the benefits are lost again.
Also here a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach up to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, therefore, a 50 x 60 cm pillow appears, as the Scandinavians like it.
In the lateral position, the head cushion (along with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Something our modern mattresses have in common with the former (filled with hay) straw bags.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
Also for mattresses, the new magic word is "Bio".
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils – for example castor oil and soybean oil – are increasingly used to produce polyurethane foams.
Soy is probably used by all known manufacturers.
"Bio is for mattresses, which consists of materials of pure natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek from the company Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was Aloe Vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scent during sleep.
There is also a difference between a man and a woman.
While in men a "cooling" plant extract from birch leaves is used so that the mattress cover can absorb the heat and cool the body, the covers have a "warming" effect for women.
Extracts from red peppermint stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex becomes pleasantly warm during sleep.
What about today’s favorites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
