The democracy movement in Latin America is getting stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
This was the result of the Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased significantly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of proponents of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since the strong collapse last year, such a trend can be seen.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with the democratic practice of their country, which is as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% trust their country’s Congress and 45% trust their government, both of which are the same as last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crisis undermined its efforts for more democracy.
This continued even during the global economic crisis, perhaps due to the fact that the countries of Latin America experienced only a short recession phase and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were captured by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
However, there are significant differences in mood from country to country (see Diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of the outgoing president Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the survey began, many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see Chart 5).
About 31% say that either they or a family member were victims of a crime in the last year. However, compared to 38% in the last year, the values have fallen and thus reach the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the stronger support to the private and market economies: around 71% of respondents said that the private economy is indispensable for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
About 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private economy), although their left-wing president, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, nationalizes many private companies.
Brazil, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), has the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the United States as the most influential country, with Venezuela taking over this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
