Arsenic-resistant microbes could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is, in their opinion, a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered life-necessary.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
“This makes it very special, although it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ life form,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online edition of Science magazine on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake continues to grow even more when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details on the discovery were announced gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements, and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically identical, she assumed that microbes that are exposed to both may be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to its chemically similar behavior to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so big that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus, it gets into our biochemical system, where it lubricates almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic, adapting and growing.
The microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based lifeform can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms used it.
“There is reason to believe that life may have evolved differently from the early Earth age,” said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
