Police interventions in China are becoming smoother
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin walked across an urban square, checking his nervous subordinates, issuing orders with military authority and a muted voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan – China’s rugged guardians of urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and their penchant for violence – to impress viewers.
"Stand up straight!"
"Look straight!"
“Show them,” he whispered to them, “how pretty girls are!”
Four girls, barely growing up in their teenage years, with white gloves and identical olive-green jackets and pants stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps were in a straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white striped loops.
"To me, they look average," Mr. Tang remarked in a slight way.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to polish up the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The province of Guangdong introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the gray-green ones.
Wuhan in central China replaced violence with low-starvation: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly surrounded an improperly positioned snack car and stared at the operator until it packed in after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a city district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been intensifying the city’s police stripes. They have been selected special because of their appearance, their good figure and their youth.
They are supposed to give the coarsely beaten police a softer, feminine aspect.
But unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would hardly be able to improve the bad image that the Chinese have of these city commandos.
Rightly so, the critics.
Unlike the police, these officials are only allowed to enforce city laws with fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely show a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei province beat a spectator to death when he filmed them using his mobile phone, beating down a protest action against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon trader suffered brain injuries after a hand mix with five officials.
A violent video game that can be downloaded from the Internet shows officials trained in China in an attack on street vendors.
"Chengguan scares the government," the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, after further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a “really thorough clean-up.”
Skeptics see the current approach as clearly inadequate.
When the district searched for eight female recruits in October by advertisement, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News asked whether the women should have real tasks or only serve as an optical distraction.
Probably both of them.
According to the job advertisement, women aged 18 to 22 with good figure and "harmonic facial features" were sought.
They should be above average size - over 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends upon reaching the age of 26.
According to officials, the activity is too physically strenuous for women over 25.
"The most important thing is their image," an unnamed district official told the quasi-government website Rednet.com.
"Whether the candidates get the job depends first on their external appearance, such as size, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes temperament and "inner qualities".
"Female Chengguan are like flower vases," he said, adding, "but beyond that, they have other duties."
Zheng Lihua, deputy head of the district's city administration, does not wish to add to this description,
However, he admitted that size specifications in job advertisements for both sexes are not uncommon in China.
The same applies to uniform facial features.
Whether this should be equated with good looks is controversial in China.
But people with disabilities or physical disabilities do not need to apply.
"Unfortunately, we can't use hams or buckligens here," said Mr. Zheng.
"Your image would not be good."
Liu Yi, who patrols the Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple berries and a well-shaped mouth.
She did not feel as sexist that so much value is placed on her appearance.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asks with an ironic look.
Her colleague with the trenches, 21-year-old Xu Yang, commented, "We have the task of representing the image of the city."
According to them, they do not regret the short-term attitude, as they had more ambitious career plans than simply shoveling traders through the streets to prevent them from doing business.
Every morning, the strip deals with about twelve street vendors who try to sell as many breads and tofu dishes as possible on foot or by bike before they are chased away.
"Mr. Wang, please get out of here."
"We have told you this so many times!" explains Fr. Xu to a trader who had fled on foot and had temporarily abandoned his noodle kitchen attached to a bicycle cart.
According to the officials, the activity is more monotonous than strenuous.
"It's almost the same every day," explains Huang Jing, 20, who studies in leisure sales.
"Everything routine."
One reason for this is that female officials are not allowed to confiscate the merchants’ goods, like their male counterparts.
They can only threaten criminals to report them to their male superiors.
This is to protect them from public hostilities, to which officials in China are often exposed.
This year, hundreds of residents of Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, ransacked after the rumor escalated that Chengguan officials had killed a trader.
More than a dozen police and Chengguan officials were injured in the nighttime incident, 14 government vehicles were toppled or set on fire.
Xindu has so far been spared such violence.
However, unrest cannot be ruled out.
Just two blocks away from the quiet Baonguang Square, where the female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered at a street corner.
Officials had confiscated a motorcycle, which was repaired contrary to the regulations on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop.
The owner shouted Zeter and Mordio.
After 15 minutes of hesitation, the officers, with grim faces, made their way to their vehicles and proceeded with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a coordinator of the male strip, stayed behind, turning his white nameplate to remain anonymous.
Like their colleagues, the coordinators – men over 40 – play a purely supportive role.
But they were not trained to present a clean image.
"Sometimes we go verbally."
"But sometimes also physically," Mr. Li explains soberly.
“Most of the time, people start arguing.”
