Can courtesy connect the separating?
After a campaign of slander and negativity, little courtesy has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough in the major issues that had to be dealt with during the so-called “lame duck session” at the end of a government term in which decisions are no longer being made.
According to all that is heard, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an observance of their shared responsibility, but rather an empty episode of a party point collection.
The public meeting of the President's deficit committee on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect, which obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate members from each other.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one calls for the other sign of cooperation and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a new party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November election in Washington has been a mild one, at least for a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed," said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
In some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one favors that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on the rise in unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying unemployment workers support.
After the meeting on Tuesday in the White House, optimism has increased that these issues can be agreed during the "lame duck session" and at the same time the New START Treaty can be ratified.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session" does not necessarily lead to permanent cooperation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – courtesy leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what is happening from today to 2012, as a foreplay, or shadowboxing, for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the emergence of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their formation.
As worried as Republican leaders may be that they are playing poker too high, they know that they need to try to keep their promises to cut government spending and overturn health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include a tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of the retirement age and the lowering of government spending.
Vice-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and have, in their own estimation, pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that they can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes in the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling very hard to get even close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the Board, because in financial matters, at least today, there is little room or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will take place next year in the form of party clashes if the Republicans challenge Obama regarding the state budget, taxes and the health care system, later followed by a phase of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as it did in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partiality and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more consequential election in 2012.
In this way, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
U.S. document leaked portrays Moscow as a port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the "kleptocracy" and it passes part of the bribery and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, the American embassy in Russia reported in a memo in February.
Both the police and the state security service are blackmailing high protection funds so that they can maintain their expensive standard of living in Moscow, it is said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal gangs.
Every layer of bureaucracy — what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “verticals of authority” — takes its share of the money that heads up.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its homepage on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names were edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still the mayor of Moscow, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired by President Dmitry Medvedev in October, but there is little evidence that he had been cleared in the meantime.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won numerous libel lawsuits against such accusations.
In September, he told a Russian television station when asked for documentation suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s dirty, it’s dirty.”
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual that, as happened in the Ambassador’s report, individuals are mentioned, and it is unheard of that this is done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
“The direct association of the Moscow government with crime has led some to call it ‘disrupted’ and conclude that the government acts more like a kleptocrat than a government,” the memo said.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'kryshna' (a term from the world of criminals/mafia, literally meaning 'roof' or protection) that extends across the police, the State Security (FSB), the Service Supervisory Authority (MVD) and the Office of the Prosecutor as well as throughout the entire Moscow government.
Experts have discovered a three-layer structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is in the top spot."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are at the second level."
"Recently, ordinary criminals and criminal inspectors follow at the lowest level."
"This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups in some areas close a gap because the city does not offer any help."
The report goes on to say that the FSB is cashing money from the biggest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source, it is said, “explained that Moscow business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime) because they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is no longer in demand as before.”
The memo notes that while fundraising is extensive, the protection itself is not very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who don’t pay find their business closed very quickly – due to one or the other pretext.
Medvedev has repeatedly spoken about fighting corruption, but at the same time noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the embassy contains descriptions of men who went to the Kremlin with suitcases that were presumably full of money.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on the bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow expert commission, said in an interview recently.
"But he's part of that bureaucracy."
"It is not part of the political class because a political class in Russia no longer exists."
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, Indem estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey of the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are listed from “the least corrupt” to “the most corrupt”).
The unveiling of the memo of the American embassy, which took place late in the evening after Moscow time, will certainly trigger mishaps within the Russian government, although, since Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow’s mistakes, there may also be a possibility for the Kremlin to claim that the problems are being solved.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fake and reacted angryly to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth is that it’s about our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policy in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest, we didn’t expect this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure and in such an unethical way, you know.”
