China maintains its targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of China stated at COP16 that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is keeping its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
At his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said his country has invested $245 million over the past four years to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its objectives, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programs.
In all aspects, progress has been made, including the adoption of a new energy law last year that includes the targets for reducing emissions of gases, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states worked with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he argued, several multi-year plans have already been launched or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which was introduced over the last five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and from private hands.
There is also a project at provincial level on climate change, another to replace traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs and another to weaken and adapt, he explained.
Martin Krol, the country’s scientific advisor to the government on climate change, confirmed that China’s efforts would be far greater than commonly thought.
He pointed out that the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amount to six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent overall contribution to environmental pollution.
It also makes unprecedented progress in the field of energy use: energy efficiency has increased by twenty percent in the last five years, and another one is expected to happen by 2020, he said.
