The United States changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves before their conversation with the consulate at the services for the visa application; costs will be waiting times will be shortened thus.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa application services (ASCs, the initial letters in English) prior to their conversation at the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the Consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases, as it is no longer necessary to pay the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out separately.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the opposite of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only need to introduce themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those applying for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
