Global Plan for the Renewal of Lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan to renew lighting for households, trade and industry in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG), which corresponds to almost one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented to stabilize the Earth’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan occupies its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments of the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of FCKW emitted to the earth due to the lighting would be avoided if the white glowing bulbs, which until now still represent a 50 to 70% monopoly on the market, were set by fluorescent or better, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to the equivalent of 70% of the global fleet’s exhaust gases.
In Copenhagen last year, major exhaust gas emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CHP emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would still have to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020, to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs this energy demand is again reduced by twice.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week - this company has participated in the UN study by the way - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white incandescent bulb, which is intended to convey an indication of the savings possibilities of the replacement plan.
In addition to the fact that esee completely novel bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they need to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide an acceptance point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the gains that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars a year on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
