The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has emerged as an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of sanctity that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's move on.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (of any x-nation) consists exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what has been read in any newspaper for months anyway (except for those whose owner is Berlusconi), and the appallingly caricatured profile of Stdafi's offered to Kaba.
The rule that the secret files should consist only of news already known is essential for the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will realize that each work (about the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (yet because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown’s success mechanism.
The same goes for the secret acts.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited minded) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who considers only what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome had sent to the State Dezernat was the same as those that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was such a reversal made around the disclosures of these dossiers?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely, that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then the heads of government have been able to call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representational tasks, have given themselves up to spoofing.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one does so to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that an x-any hacker can capture the most secretive secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the State Dezernat.
In addition, the scandal brings fewer victims than rather the "sharp judges" in distress.
But let us dedicate ourselves to the profound nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, one could bundle all power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where you can control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if you look at what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control loop stops being one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker—chosen as the citizen’s avenger—can uncover the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free from secrecy, as it was to reveal the public sphere of WikiLeaks that I was leaking to Le Hill;
