Climate: how France talks about its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the rapidly resolved financing promises (also called “fast start” or early funding) realised by the developing countries.
And the coarse French beauties have already been uncovered.
The Copenhagen Treaty commits developing countries to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years, France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn all the registers to convince its partners of the fact of their commitment to fast-start funding: detailed progress report of their Member States, press conference, major side events, distribution of brochures.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and highly valued for its true value: developing countries and civil society like to see all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had mobilised <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to pay the 7.2 billion it pledged in 2012.
But when you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" in order to ensure that additional spending has been made without detrimental to public development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline value that they consider to be the best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen itself as the benchmark for 2009: international funding will be maintained, and the fast-start funding will add 150 million over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of public development assistance.
In return, France was of the opinion that the funding of "all new projects" of 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words: there are no guide values for the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of public development assistance.
Concretely, the overall amount of French aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" funding.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> as the equivalent of 1 donated <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>.
Obviously, this is only difficult to bear: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often linked to the emission reduction of projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro, which is taken as the equivalent of a donated euro. In addition, the cost of the loan should be taken as the equivalent of the amount of the loan.
But France has nothing but the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros, by taking 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans to a large extent.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are 100% complying with their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to fulfil its obligations, France just gives 10 cents and understands a comparable use.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double fraud: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in line with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who conducted the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once inside the EU (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to lend?) and then in the negotiations, as the developing countries do not completely let go...
The chapter of early funding is only a small question in a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions on the climate.
But it could be too much of a drop in the UNFCCC’s immense machinery.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn his lesson from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and of balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could put forward discussions on the disputed subject of long-term financing (another crucial and currently debated topic): the question of "predictability" or the way in which its loans are accounted for cannot be avoided.
