Alarm - pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child takes 81 different chemicals over the course of the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Générations Futures Association (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "given the small number of samples analyzed do not reflect a statistically significant value, but represent an illustrative character of the issue treated", had between July and September the typically within four, from about a ten-year-old child to meals consumed food plus an O-meal at the supermarkets.
These typical meals—including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and vegetable parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day—were examined as well as dairies from laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The plate balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, including 42 classified as potentially or likely carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if, in the approximate totality of cases, the legal limits for each chemical, individually ingested substance are not exceeded, it is very well understood from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine-disrupting factor is a concern."
Already at breakfast, the butter and the tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
